h3. Problem Definition

Lot of Content search queries as below are issued when accessed via REST content api.
{code:sql}
select abstractpa0_.CONTENTID as CONTENTI1_12_, .... from CONTENT abstractpa0_ 
... limit 500, 501;
select abstractpa0_.CONTENTID as CONTENTI1_12_, .... from CONTENT abstractpa0_ 
... limit 1000, 501;
select abstractpa0_.CONTENTID as CONTENTI1_12_, .... from CONTENT abstractpa0_ 
... limit 1500, 501;
.....
select abstractpa0_.CONTENTID as CONTENTI1_12_, .... from CONTENT abstractpa0_ 
... limit 10000, 501;
{code}
h3. How to replicate this problem

There are at least two types of scenario to cause this problem –
 *Scenario 1*
 # Create a Confluence Instance with many content. e.g. 20,000 content.
 # Create a user who has access permission to the contents created in step 1. e.g. testuser
 # Clear cache
 # Send a GET request with {{rest/api/content?start=<any number over 500>}} to the instance. e.g. start from 10,000
{code:java}
curl -u testuser:testuser http://<confluence-base-url>/rest/api/content?start=10000
{code}

i.e. Confluence tries to fetch all 10,500 contents to obtain just 500 contents from 10,001st to 10,500th items.

*Scenario 2*
 # Create a Confluence Instance with many content. e.g. 20,000 content.
 # Create a user who *doesn't* have access permission to the contents created in step 1. e.g. testuser
 # Clear cache
 # Send a GET request with {{rest/api/content}} to the instance.
{code:java}
curl -u testuser:testuser http://<confluence-base-url>/rest/api/content
{code}

i.e. Confluence tries to fetch all 20,000 contents to filter the contents on which the testuser has permission.
h3. Suggested Solution

For scenario 1, to obtain data for {{rest/api/content?start=10000}} , *only* the query
{code:java}
select abstractpa0_.CONTENTID as CONTENTI1_12_, .... from CONTENT abstractpa0_ 
... limit 10000, 501;
{code}
should be issued.

For scenario 2, filter the CONTENT first with permission and fetch the items later.
h3. Why this is important

Because this can cause a performance problem on database server processing a lot of queries at the same time.

h3. Summary
Side-by-side sections on a Confluence page will show as on top of each other when exported to HTML.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page that has a [page layout|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/page-layouts-columns-and-sections-275188613.html] section with multiple columns.
!page-layout-editor.png|thumbnail!
# Save the page
!page-layout-saved.png|thumbnail!
# Export the space to HTML
# View the page

h3. Expected Results
The sections will show side-by-side, as they do on the page.

h3. Actual Results
The sections are stacked on top of each other.
!page-layout-html-export.png|thumbnail!

h3.Workaround
Add the following at the end of the styles/site.css file in the export:
{code:css}
.columnLayout {
    display: flex;
}

.cell {
    flex: auto;
}
{code}
